issue.title: How to disable electron generate zip.blockmap?
issue.body:
[![enter image description here][1]][1]


  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/tmODO.png

I am using electron-builder to build mac and windows app. Abouve is my electron build output directory. I don't need autoupdater. So I just wanna `.dmg` and `.exe` files. How can I set `builder` config to diable electron generate those useless files(yal、yaml、zip、zip.blockmap)?

Below is my package.json
```json
  "build": {
    "appId": "we-media-helper",
    "copyright": "Copyright © 2022 Eve-Sama",
    "generateUpdatesFilesForAllChannels": true,
    "directories": {
      "output": "./dist/installer"
    },
    "mac": {
      "target": {
        "target": "default",
        "arch": [
          "arm64",
          "x64",
          "universal"
        ]
      },
      "icon": "./assets/icons/mac-dock.icns",
      "publish": {
        "owner": "Eve-Sama",
        "repo": "we-media-helper",
        "provider": "github"
      }
    },
    "dmg": {
      "writeUpdateInfo": false
    },
    "nsis": {
      "differentialPackage": false,
      "oneClick": false,
      "allowElevation": true,
      "allowToChangeInstallationDirectory": true,
      "installerIcon": "./assets/icons/win-taskbar.ico",
      "uninstallerIcon": "./assets/icons/win-taskbar.ico",
      "installerHeaderIcon": "./assets/icons/win-taskbar.ico",
      "createDesktopShortcut": true,
      "createStartMenuShortcut": true,
      "artifactName": "${productName}_Setup_${version}.${ext}"
    },
    "win": {
      "icon": "./assets/icons/win-taskbar.ico",
      "target": [
        {
          "target": "nsis",
          "arch": [
            "ia32"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "files": [
      "**/*",
      "!dist/installer",
      "!**/*.ts",
      "!**/*.tsx",
      "!src/",
      "!public/",
      "!.eslintignore",
      "!.eslintrc.js",
      "!.gitignore",
      "!.prettierrc",
      "!gulpfile.ts",
      "!LICENSE",
      "!package-lock.json",
      "!README.md",
      "!tsconfig.json",
      "!yarn.lock"
    ],
    "extends": null
  },
```

And I have another question. As you can see, I set `mac.target.arch` as `['arm64', 'x64', 'universal']`. And output directory contains folder `mac` rather than `mac-x64`. why? How can I set it as `mac-x64`

issue.title: 'tool: "notarytool"' won't work
issue.body:
<!--
issue_labeler_regex_version=0
-->

<!-- Which version of electron-builder are you using? -->
<!-- Please always try to use latest version before reporting any issue. -->
* **Electron-Builder Version**: 24.6.1
* **@electron/notarize Version**: 2.1.0
* **@electron/osx-sign Version**: 1.0.4

<!-- Which version of node are you using? -->
* **Node Version**: 18.16.1

<!-- Which version of electron are you using? -->
<!-- Please verify if the error is electron related before reporting any issues. -->
* **Electron Version**: 25.3.1
* **Electron Type (current, beta, nightly)**: current
<!-- Which version of electron-updater are you using (if applicable)? -->

<!-- For which target are you building for? -->
* **Target**: macOS

<!-- Enter your issue details below this comment. -->
Legacy altool mode is used even if 'tool: "notarytool"' is specified in the notarize script.

```typescript
const notarizer = async (context: AfterPackContext) => {
  const { appOutDir } = context;
  const appName = context.packager.appInfo.productFilename;

  return await notarize({
    tool: "notarytool",
    appPath: `${appOutDir}/${appName}.app`,
    teamId: `${process.env.TEAM_ID}`,
    appleId: `${process.env.APPLE_ID}`,
    appleIdPassword: `${process.env.APPLE_APP_SPECIFIC_PASSWORD}`,
  });
};
```

Output to the console is as follows:

```sh
Notarizing using the legacy altool system. The altool system will be disabled on November 1 2023. Please switch to the notarytool system before then.
You can do this by setting "tool: notarytool" in your "@electron/notarize" options. Please note that the credentials options may be slightly different between tools.
```

comment.body: My not-perfect-but-working solution was to disable notarization in builder configuration completely, then setting up notarization script in `afterSign`.

issue.title: Icons not being detected
issue.body:
<!--
issue_labeler_regex_version=0
-->

<!-- Which version of electron-builder are you using? -->
<!-- Please always try to use latest version before reporting any issue. -->
* **Electron-Builder Version**: 24.6.3

<!-- Which version of node are you using? -->
* **Node Version**: 18.14.0

<!-- Which version of electron are you using? -->
<!-- Please verify if the error is electron related before reporting any issues. -->
* **Electron Version**: v22.2.0
* **Electron Type (current, beta, nightly)**: current
<!-- Which version of electron-updater are you using (if applicable)? -->

<!-- For which target are you building for? -->
* **Target**: Windows

<!-- Enter your issue details below this comment. -->
When building, the icons are not detected. The only available documentation for icons (since the documentation for the property is missing, see #6371) is [here](https://www.electron.build/icons), which says they must be in `buildResources` (which also is missing any documentation).

Icon location: `<project>/assets/images/app-icon.png`

`<project>/.build/client.ts`:
```typescript
// ... variable declarations, imports, etc. ...
const electronBuilderConfig: electronBuilder.CliOptions = {
	publish: 'never',
	projectDir: path.resolve(fileURLToPath(import.meta.url), '..', '..'),
	config: {
		extends: null,
		extraMetadata: {
			main: path.join(options.output, 'app.cjs'),
			version: pkg.version,
		},
		files: [_files0, 'package.json'],
		appId: 'dev.myapp',
		productName: 'myapp Client',
		copyright,
		icon: './assets/app-icon.png',
		nsis: {
			oneClick: false,
			allowToChangeInstallationDirectory: true,
			removeDefaultUninstallWelcomePage: true,
			deleteAppDataOnUninstall: true,
		},
		win: {
			icon: './assets/app-icon.png',
			executableName: 'myapp-client',
		},
		linux: {
			icon: './assets/app-icon.png',
			category: 'Game',
		},
		mac: {
			icon: './assets/app-icon.png',
			category: 'public.app-category.games',
		},
	},
};
```

issue.title: June 2023 Code Signing with HSM APIs
issue.body:
Hi

Is electron-builder able to use services like Digicert Keylocker 

https://knowledge.digicert.com/generalinformation/new-private-key-storage-requirement-for-standard-code-signing-certificates-november-2022.html  says I now need a hardware token (mine or cloud) but as I use Github Actions CI to build - I can't use a USB token so https://knowledge.digicert.com/solution/digicert-keylocker.html sounds more likely


Refer https://github.com/electron/windows-installer/issues/473#issuecomment-1581441658

Would I be able to use https://docs.digicert.com/en/digicert-one/digicert-keylocker/ci-cd-integrations/plugins/github-custom-action-for-keypair-signing.html

comment.body:
Document https://docs.digicert.com/en/digicert-keylocker/ci-cd-integrations/script-integrations/github-integration-ksp.html really helps.

Here's how is our application signed by KeyLocker: https://github.com/nervosnetwork/neuron/pull/2913

There are mainly two steps:

1. Setup signing runtime: https://github.com/nervosnetwork/neuron/pull/2913/files#diff-170ebc8e4dc40acf23cbe0ecce5f3e2aef1652511f59860db704106b197e1d52R54-R85
2. Sign application: https://github.com/nervosnetwork/neuron/pull/2913/files#diff-170ebc8e4dc40acf23cbe0ecce5f3e2aef1652511f59860db704106b197e1d52R54-R85

comment.body:
What about using?
```
[key: string]: OutgoingHttpHeader | undefined
```
It's a standard @node-type that would update as node versions update. It's a type alias for
```
    type OutgoingHttpHeader = number | string | string[];
```
